GamesRegularyPlayed: skyrim, call of duty, fallout, gta, civilization, overcooked, little big planet, horizon zero dawn, the last of us
DS: i find the delay sensitivity to be very high since a fraction of a second of delay could mean losing the game (high consequence)
TA: shots can be fired several times per second by each player, and targets are moving so reaction time is very short for each individual player
SA: I'd say moderate because the crosshairs of the weapon are at least a third of the size of the target when within shooting range, so a player with modest experience shouldn't have much trouble with landing a hit
PR: Somewhere between difficult to predict and not predictable. The actions in this game are entirely dependent on other players, so i don't think one can realistically expect to win by predicting events as much as one could expect to win based on reaction time and luck
DoF: you can move in four directions on the plain while simultaneously moving the camera and shooting
CQ: incorrect interactions would mean getting shot at which result in dying and losing the game
IoA: every shot counts towards killing the enemy which make the stakes really high for every shot taken
RA: somewhere between moderate and high. You dont necessarily need many actions per second but if confronted with many enemies you technically could use many actions per second.
FF: it's a dynamic game with many inputs coming from different sources (building, moving while shooting, getting shot at by an enemy, etc.)
ToI: the cursor is being moved for shootign while moving and i assume also for building walls
Open: specifically the relationship between the different aspects and how the play together to create an original gaming experience
